<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n56195g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56195g">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56195g"> 195(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sodium chloride ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Chlorine is not found in the free state in nature, but we can get it from a useful compound which contains it&mdash;viz. common salt. This body, which we use to flavour our food, and which gives the saltness to sea water, is made up of chlorine and the metal sodium, and common salt is therefore called chloride of sodium, or <mark>sodium chloride</mark>. <small> H. E. Roscoe, <a name="HERC3" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#HERC3"><cite title="source">Science Primer: Chemistry</cite></a> (n.d.) 84</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
